Eualesina in 8 we should correct to theuulesina ,· the e or ἐ represents the Umlaut of 0 or oo, better written ω, as it is not likely that such an Umlaut was pronounced in another manner than it is at present in the Frankish and most Saxon dialects, or in M. H. G. and M. D. It is just possible that e is an innovation ol the scribes, who, being in the habit of replacing even a Latin oe by e (²), saw no harm in doing the same for the F rank. In Latin documents of the Frank kings we repeatedly find names of well-known places in the Netherlands containing the oe (spelt eu in D.) written with i, e. g. Lis-idun, now-a-days Leusden. In short, a real e or i, sounded as such, in cases where the Umlaut of 0 or oo is required, would be an anachronism in any ancient Frankish, Saxon, or High-German dialect. In A. S. and Frisian the case is quite different, of course. Theulasina in 10 wants no further com- ment; it shows the usual orthography of the cod„ and is therefore genuine. The reverse is the case with theolasina uuirtico, which has been added from another source, the same from which 6 is derived.
